Bona fides implies the absence of dolus: so far then as the exceptio merely empowered the judex to take into consideration equitable grounds of defense, no exceptio doli was necessary in actions bonae fidei, for here the commission ol the judex expresrdy authorized him in the intentio of the formula to decide upon equitable grounds (ex bona fidel: Judicium fidei bonae est et continet in se doli muli exceptionem, Dig. 30, 84, 5: Cum enim doli exceptio insit de dote actioni, utin esteris bonae fidei judiciis, Dig. 24, 3, 21. This, however, does not apply to the exceptio mi in judicium deductae or rei judicatae and others like exceptio cognitor-ia and litis dividuae, which are founded rather on special consideratione thau on those relating to bona fides, and had to be expressed in the formula, if they formed the defence of the defendant, even in actions bonae fidei. (Of. Keller, Civil Process, ,t 35.)

Cicero gives the form of exceptio doli contained in the edictum Asiaticum of Q. Mucius: Extra quam si ita negotium gestum eet ut eo stari non oporteat ex fids bona, Ad Att 6, 1, ‘unless ths circum· stances of the disposition make its enforcement inconsistent with the principles of good faith' This seems to be impersonally named, but the formula, as stated, may be incomplete. (cf. Dig. 44, 4, 2, 1.)

The exceptio doli from the comprehensiveness of its meaning. does not sufficiently disclose the line of defence which a defendant intends to pursue: accordingly, in Germany, the fact which mn· stitutes the dolus is always required to be specified.
